/* 
  Algorithm: Greedy simulation with a single current charm's HP.
  Key idea: fight whenever curHP >= next enemy; otherwise charm.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n;
    if (!(cin >> n)) return 0;
    vector<int> hp(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> hp[i];
    }

    int charms = 0;
    int curHP = 0;
    int i = 0;
    while (i < n) {
        if (curHP == 0) {
            // Must charm the next enemy to start fighting
            curHP = hp[i++];
            charms++;
        } else {
            if (curHP >= hp[i]) {
                // Fight and kill the enemy
                curHP -= hp[i++];
            } else {
                // Our charm would die; better to charm this enemy first
                curHP = hp[i++];
                charms++;
            }
        }
    }

    cout << charms << "\n";
    return 0;
}

[Error Message]
答案错误

[Defect Analysis Report]
[Defect Analysis Report]
1. Inferred Defect Type:  
   Logical flaw in the greedy simulation (incorrect state management of the “charmed” queue).

2. Suspicious Code Segment(s):  
   In the main while‐loop (around lines 31–41 of the snippet):
   ```
   if (curHP == 0) {
       // Must charm the next enemy to start fighting
       curHP = hp[i++];
       charms++;
   } else {
       if (curHP >= hp[i]) {
           // Fight and kill the enemy
           curHP -= hp[i++];
       } else {
           // Our charm would die; better to charm this enemy first
           curHP = hp[i++];
           charms++;
       }
   }
   ```
   – In particular the branch “else … curHP = hp[i++]”: it overwrites/discards the previous `curHP` rather than queueing it behind the newly charmed zombie.

3. Root Cause Explanation:  
   The problem statement specifies that each time you charm an enemy it joins the back of your own zombie‐queue, and the existing front zombies are not lost until they actually fight and die. The submitted code, however, maintains only a single “current” friendly HP in `curHP`. Whenever it decides to charm a new zombie (even if there was still leftover HP in `curHP`), it throws away the old `curHP` and replaces it. This loses the benefit of earlier charmed zombies and can force extra charms later.

4. Possible Triggering Scenario:  
   Any input where you charm a weaker enemy first, accumulate some leftover HP, but then encounter a stronger enemy where you should enqueue (but not discard) your current fighter. For example:
     – n=6, sequence = [2, 5, 1, 3, 2, 4]  
     The greedy code will overwrite the 2‐HP charm when it sees the 5, losing that 2‐HP unit forever, whereas the correct strategy would be to queue both 2 and 5 and use them later.

[Fix Suggestions]
1. Correction Strategy:  
   a. Model your own queue explicitly. Use a queue or deque `myQ` to store the HPs of all charmed zombies in order.  
   b. Every time you “charm,” do:  
      ```
      myQ.push_back(hp[i++]);
      charms++;
      ```  
   c. Whenever both `enemyQ` (or just the array with index `i`) and `myQ` are non‐empty, simulate the head‐to‐head fight:
      ```
      while (i < n && !myQ.empty()) {
        int e = hp[i], f = myQ.front();
        if (f >= e) {
          myQ.front() = f - e;
          if (myQ.front() == 0) myQ.pop_front();
          i++;
        } else {
          // friendly dies
          myQ.pop_front();
        }
      }
      ```
   d. When `myQ` becomes empty but `i<n`, you must charm at least once to get a new front.  
   This corrects the state management: you never discard a living charmed zombie until it actually fights and is killed.

2. Risk Warning (Optional):  
   - A naive full‐queue simulation can be O(n²) in the worst case if every fight only shaves off 1 HP at a time. To stay within time limits for n ≈ 6400 and hp up to 6400, you may need to optimize by:  
     • Amortizing the fight loop, or  
     • Aggregating consecutive smaller fights, or  
     • Employing a two‐pointer technique to skip zero‐sum fights.  

3. Verification Method:  
   - Test small handcrafted cases, especially where multiple charmed zombies stack before any fight:
     • Increasing sequences (e.g. [1,2,3,…])  
