After reviewing the defect report and the sample‐failing behavior, the root cause is that our “bulk‐fight” transitions (from a batch of k charmed zombies all the way to whichever side empties first) never allow “pausing” after a single head‐to‐head fight to cast another charm.  The problem statement explicitly permits you to charm either immediately before or immediately after *each single* front‐zombie clash, but our aggregate simulation only ever produces end‐of‐bulk outcomes—thus it misses interleavings that can reduce the total number of charms.

To fix this while preserving the overall structure, we
1. Switch from plain Dijkstra to a 0–1 BFS (deque), because we have exactly two kinds of moves:  
   a. a **fight** between the front of your queue and the front of the enemy queue (cost 0),  
   b. a **single charm** of exactly one enemy head into your queue (cost 1).  
2. We explicitly track the two‐dimensional state `(pos, h)` where  
   – `pos` is the index of the next uncharmed enemy in the original array,  
   – `h` is the residual health of that current enemy head (0 ≤ h ≤ 6400, with h=0 indicating “no partial head; the next real hp[pos] is the head”).  
   The friendly‐queue is always implicit: you only ever need to know its current‐front health to do one fight, and we restore the previous front automatically because you never “bulk-accumulate” charms—each charm pushes exactly one new head, which you either fight immediately (0-cost) or you can fight before charming again.  
3. We implement two transitions per state `(pos,h)`:  
   – **Charm transition** (cost 1): remove the enemy head `(pos,h)` and replace it by pushing it into your (implicit) queue.  Concretely, if `h>0`, that head is removed and we set the next enemy‐head `h′=hp[pos]` (or 0 if `pos+1>n`), and we increase `pos` only once `h` was 0.  We mark that after the charm, our *friendly* front has health `h`, and the *enemy* front becomes `(pos′,h′)`.  We then immediately follow that with a **fight** edge (cost 0) in the same iteration.  
   – **Fight transition** (cost 0): if both your front and the enemy front exist, we simulate exactly one fight: compare your current head‐HP `f` and the enemy head‐HP `e`, subtract the smaller from the larger, drop whoever hits zero, and update `(pos,h)` accordingly.  We push that into the front of the deque.  

Because every charm is cost 1 and every single fight is cost 0, a 0–1 BFS on the grid `(pos,h,f)` degenerates neatly to a 2D `(pos,h)` with an on‐the‐fly `f` popped from a small separate array.  The total number of states is O(n·H), and each state has only two outgoing edges, so the solution runs in O(n·H).

The key conceptual change is: **we no longer “bulk‐simulate” a chunk of fights in one go; we break it up so that after each single‐zombie fight we return to the BFS and allow a charm.**  This faithfully models the “before or after each fight” rule, and on the sample it now finds 3 charms.

